SIMPLE: tumble
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tumble
<hw>Tum"ble</hw> <pr>(t⟦ucr⟧m"b'l)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Tumbled</conjf>
<pr>(t⟦ucr⟧m"b'ld)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Tumbling</conjf> <pr>(t⟦ucr⟧m"bl⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph>
<ety>[OE. <ets>tumblen</ets>, AS. <ets>tumbian</ets> to turn heels over
head, to dance violently; akin to D. <ets>tuimelen</ets> to fall, Sw.
<ets>tumla</ets>, Dan. <ets>tumle</ets>, Icel. <ets>tumba</ets>; and cf.
G. <ets>taumeln</ets> to reel, to stagger.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
roll over, or to and fro; to throw one's self about; <as>as, a person in
pain <ex>tumbles</ex> and tosses</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To roll down; to fall suddenly and violently; to be
precipitated; <as>as, to <ex>tumble</ex> from a scaffold</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He who <qex>tumbles</qex> from a tower surely has a greater blow
than he who slides from a molehill.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To play tricks by various movements and contortions
of the body; to perform the feats of an acrobat.</def>
<rj><au>Rowe.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To tumble home</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to
incline inward, as the sides of a vessel, above the bends or extreme
breadth; -- used esp. in the phrase <xex>tumbling home</xex>. Cf.
<er>Wall-sided</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tumble</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Tumble
<hw>Tum"ble</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To turn over; to
turn or throw about, as for examination or search; to roll or move in a
rough, coarse, or unceremonious manner; to throw down or headlong; to
precipitate; -- sometimes with <xex>over</xex>, <xex>about</xex>, etc.;
<as>as, to <ex>tumble</ex> books or papers</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To disturb; to rumple; <as>as, to <ex>tumble</ex> a
bed</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tumble</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Tumble
<hw>Tum"ble</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Act of tumbling, or rolling over; a
fall.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tumblebug</ent>⟦br⟧
